ral and material contexts, and showing how it explores medieval anxieties concerning salvation and identity. The author argues that the legend is a sustained meditation on the power of images, its popularity corresponding with the rise of their role in portraying medieval identity and salvation, and in acting as portals between the limits of the material and the possibilities of the spiritual world Jerry Root is Associate Professor of French and Comparative Literature, University of Utah.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 4aArt & Architecture. 4aFrench Studies. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aART / European.2bisacsh  aAdgar.  aChristianity.  aGautier de Coinci.  aLegend.  aMedieval history.  aMedieval literature.  aMedieval religion.  aMedieval text.  aMiddle Ages.  aMiracles of the Virgin.  aPaul the Deacon.  aRutebeuf.  aTheophilus.  amedieval identity.  amedieval manuscripts.  avisual culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440098423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787440098/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles